{"type": "assistant", "message": {"model": "claude-sonnet-4-6", "id": "msg_vrtx_01E3i4hijhn8WAkbtB5Qxx49", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "tool_use", "id": "toolu_vrtx_01CyromTzXZ8oGomFEtaiTZH", "name": "Write", "input": {"file_path": "/Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/nielsens-10-usability-heuristics.md", "content": "# Nielsen's 10 Usability Heuristics\n\nFoundational UX design principles by Jakob Nielsen (1994), refined from 249 usability problems. Used as the base rubric for heuristic evaluation and automated prototype assessment.\n\n## Key Points\n\n- **1 \u2014 Visibility of System Status**: Always inform users about what's happening; feedback should be timely and predictable \u2014 builds trust\n- **2 \u2014 Match System to Real World**: Use language and concepts familiar to users, not internal jargon; follow real-world conventions and natural mapping\n- **3 \u2014 User Control and Freedom**: Provide clear \"emergency exits\" (undo/redo, cancel); prevents users from feeling trapped by accidental actions\n- **4 \u2014 Consistency and Standards**: Don't make users guess if different words/actions mean the same thing; follow platform conventions (Jakob's Law: users spend most time on other products)\n- **5 \u2014 Error Prevention**: Prevent problems first; two error types \u2014 slips (unconscious, inattention) and mistakes (mental model mismatch); use constraints and good defaults\n- **6 \u2014 Recognition Rather than Recall**: Make elements/actions/options visible; don't force users to remember info across interface sections; limited short-term memory\n- **7 \u2014 Flexibility and Efficiency**: Provide accelerators (shortcuts, gestures) for experts while keeping the interface accessible to novices; allow customization\n- **8 \u2014 Aesthetic and Minimalist Design**: Every extra info unit competes with relevant content; not about flat design \u2014 about keeping visual elements focused on user goals\n- **9 \u2014 Help Recover from Errors**: Error messages in plain language, precisely identify the problem, constructively suggest a solution; use visual treatments to make errors noticeable\n- **10 \u2014 Help and Documentation**: Best if no docs needed; when required \u2014 searchable, task-focused, concise, with concrete steps\n- Originally developed with Rolf Molich (1990); refined via factor analysis of 249 problems (1994); unchanged since then\n- Severity ratings 1\u20134 commonly used when applying heuristics to specific interfaces\n\n## Related\n\n- [Nielsen's Heuristics & The Jagged Edge](nielsens-heuristics-jagged-edge.md) \u2014 applied these heuristics in an AI model comparison across Cursor, Claude Code, Gemini, and ChatGPT\n- [UX Quality Rubric](ux-quality-rubric.md) \u2014 usability dimension is grounded in these heuristics\n- [Evaluator Super Agent](evaluator-super-agent.md) \u2014 automated prototype evaluation uses heuristics as scoring framework\n- [Weekly Design Sync \u2014 July 1](weekly-design-sync-2026-07-01.md) \u2014 team adopted Nielsen's heuristics as base rubric for evaluations\n\n## Sources\n\n- https://www.nngroup.com/articles/ten-usability-heuristics/\n- Ingested: 2026-07-09\n"}}], "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "stop_details": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 1, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 7150, "cache_read_input_tokens": 43297, "cache_creation": {"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens": 7150, "ephemeral_1h_input_tokens": 0}, "output_tokens": 8}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "6105c313-2c53-4f04-88a6-2b3c3c60cfc6", "uuid": "2079e9eb-87e9-47d7-97cc-8cc847783534", "request_id": "req_vrtx_011Ccrm9yVjV8iomFUCTnhpf", "timestamp": "2026-07-09T16:00:48.090Z"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01CyromTzXZ8oGomFEtaiTZH","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/nielsens-10-usability-heuristics.md (file state is current in your context — no need to Read it back)"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6105c313-2c53-4f04-88a6-2b3c3c60cfc6","uuid":"0a733d53-0c6a-49c0-bfc2-9b6772314a72","timestamp":"2026-07-09T16:00:48.100Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/nielsens-10-usability-heuristics.md","content":"# Nielsen's 10 Usability Heuristics\n\nFoundational UX design principles by Jakob Nielsen (1994), refined from 249 usability problems. Used as the base rubric for heuristic evaluation and automated prototype assessment.\n\n## Key Points\n\n- **1 — Visibility of System Status**: Always inform users about what's happening; feedback should be timely and predictable — builds trust\n- **2 — Match System to Real World**: Use language and concepts familiar to users, not internal jargon; follow real-world conventions and natural mapping\n- **3 — User Control and Freedom**: Provide clear \"emergency exits\" (undo/redo, cancel); prevents users from feeling trapped by accidental actions\n- **4 — Consistency and Standards**: Don't make users guess if different words/actions mean the same thing; follow platform conventions (Jakob's Law: users spend most time on other products)\n- **5 — Error Prevention**: Prevent problems first; two error types — slips (unconscious, inattention) and mistakes (mental model mismatch); use constraints and good defaults\n- **6 — Recognition Rather than Recall**: Make elements/actions/options visible; don't force users to remember info across interface sections; limited short-term memory\n- **7 — Flexibility and Efficiency**: Provide accelerators (shortcuts, gestures) for experts while keeping the interface accessible to novices; allow customization\n- **8 — Aesthetic and Minimalist Design**: Every extra info unit competes with relevant content; not about flat design — about keeping visual elements focused on user goals\n- **9 — Help Recover from Errors**: Error messages in plain language, precisely identify the problem, constructively suggest a solution; use visual treatments to make errors noticeable\n- **10 — Help and Documentation**: Best if no docs needed; when required — searchable, task-focused, concise, with concrete steps\n- Originally developed with Rolf Molich (1990); refined via factor analysis of 249 problems (1994); unchanged since then\n- Severity ratings 1–4 commonly used when applying heuristics to specific interfaces\n\n## Related\n\n- [Nielsen's Heuristics & The Jagged Edge](nielsens-heuristics-jagged-edge.md) — applied these heuristics in an AI model comparison across Cursor, Claude Code, Gemini, and ChatGPT\n- [UX Quality Rubric](ux-quality-rubric.md) — usability dimension is grounded in these heuristics\n- [Evaluator Super Agent](evaluator-super-agent.md) — automated prototype evaluation uses heuristics as scoring framework\n- [Weekly Design Sync — July 1](weekly-design-sync-2026-07-01.md) — team adopted Nielsen's heuristics as base rubric for evaluations\n\n## Sources\n\n- https://www.nngroup.com/articles/ten-usability-heuristics/\n- Ingested: 2026-07-09\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
